%[text] # A03: QSAR Regression  -- Predicting LogP from Molecular Descriptors
%[text] EasyMolKit Analytics  -- Layer 3
%[text] LogP (the logarithm of the octanol-water partition coefficient) is a crucial physicochemical property that determines whether a drug can pass through lipid membranes and be absorbed into the body.
%[text] Experimental measurement requires compound synthesis and liquid-liquid partition assays, which are costly and time-consuming.
%[text] If LogP can be predicted from just 8 structural descriptors, thousands of candidates can be screened virtually before any compound is synthesized.
%[text] In this tutorial, we build two models -- linear regression (`fitlm`) and random forest (`fitrensemble`) -- and compare them objectively using 5-fold cross-validation.
%[text] ### What You Will Learn in This Tutorial
%[text] - Understand the importance of QSAR regression in early drug discovery
%[text] - Build and interpret a linear regression model using `fitlm()`
%[text] - Perform nonlinear ensemble (random forest) regression using `fitrensemble()`
%[text] - Apply $k$-fold cross-validation to estimate generalization performance
%[text] - Compare models using $R^2$, RMSE, and observed vs predicted plots
%[text] - Understand the concept of Applicability Domain \
%[text] ### Prerequisites
%[text] - Completion of F02 (Property Calculation)  -- Basics of Descriptors
%[text] - Recommended: A01 (Chemical Space PCA) to understand descriptor context
%[text] - Statistics and Machine Learning Toolbox (`fitlm`, `fitrensemble`, `cvpartition`)
%[text] - No internet connection required \
%[text] Estimated time required: 30-45 minutes
%[text] ### Data:
%[text] - `data/list/fda_drugs.csv`  -- 200 FDA-approved drugs (ChEMBL, CC-BY-SA 3.0)
%[text] - The ALogP column contains Crippen-Wildman estimates stored in ChEMBL, used as the target variable ("ground truth") for regression in this exercise. \
%[text] ### References
%[text] - Wildman SA & Crippen GM (1999) Prediction of physicochemical parameters by atomic contributions. J Chem Inf Comput Sci 39:868-873. doi:10.1021/ci990307l
%[text] - Breiman L (2001) Random forests. Machine Learning 45:5-32. doi:10.1023/A:1010933404324
%[text] - Cherkasov A et al. (2014) QSAR modeling: where have you been? J Med Chem 57:4977-5010. doi:10.1021/jm4004285
%[text] - Oprea TI (2000) Property distribution of drug-related chemical databases. J Comput Aided Mol Des 14:251-264. doi:10.1023/A:1008130001697 \
%[text] How to Run: Execute each section one by one with Ctrl+Enter.
%%
%[text] ## Section 0: Setup
% Resolve project root (works for Desktop, MCP, and MATLAB Online)
sDir = fileparts(mfilename('fullpath'));
if strlength(sDir) > 0
    addpath(genpath(fullfile(sDir, '..', '..', '..', 'src')));
elseif isfolder(fullfile(pwd, 'src'))
    addpath(genpath(fullfile(pwd, 'src')));
elseif ~isempty(which("logInfo"))
    addpath(genpath(fileparts(fileparts(which("logInfo")))));
end
projectRoot = resolveProjectRoot();
addpath(genpath(fullfile(projectRoot, 'src')));
logSection("A03", "Section 0: Setup", "Analytics L3"); %[output:1496bdf4]
emk.setup.initPython(); %[output:33f50401]
%[text] Warm up Python and RDKit processes (the first call takes a few seconds).
mol_warmup = emk.mol.fromSmiles("C");   % Methane -- lightweight
clear mol_warmup;
%%
%[text] ## Section 1: Loading FDA-approved drugs and calculating descriptors
%[text] We begin by computing 8 structural descriptors for each molecule to build the feature matrix $X$, then pair each row with its ALogP value as the target $y$.
%[text] ### Why exclude LogP from the features?
%[text] The target variable is ALogP (ChEMBL's Crippen-Wildman estimate).
%[text] RDKit's built-in LogP descriptor also uses the same Crippen-Wildman method, so including it as a feature would result in a trivial model of "predicting LogP from LogP," which is not meaningful for QSAR (Quantitative Structure-Activity Relationship).
%[text] Instead, use 8 complementary descriptors that encode molecular structure without directly representing lipophilicity.
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Descriptor | Category | Chemical Meaning |
%[text] | --- | --- | --- |
%[text] | MolWt | Size | Molecular weight (g/mol) |
%[text] | HeavyAtomCount | Size | Number of non-hydrogen atoms |
%[text] | TPSA | Polarity | Topological Polar Surface Area (total area of polar groups, A^2) |
%[text] | NumHDonors | Polarity | Number of hydrogen bond donors (-OH, -NH, etc.) |
%[text] | NumHAcceptors | Polarity | Number of hydrogen bond acceptors (-O-, -N-, etc.) |
%[text] | NumRotatableBonds | Topology | Number of rotatable bonds: indicator of molecular flexibility |
%[text] | RingCount | Topology | Number of rings |
%[text] | FractionCSP3 | Shape | Fraction of sp3 carbons: indicator of 3D structural complexity |
%[text:table]
%[text] Notice the chemical logic behind these correlations with LogP:
%[text] - High TPSA, HBD, HBA: more polar -\> lower LogP (increased aqueous solubility).
%[text] - High FractionCSP3: more 3D character -\> lower planarity -\> lower LogP.
%[text] - Larger MolWt shows a weak positive correlation with LogP within drug-like chemical space. \
DATA_FILE  = "data/list/fda_drugs.csv";
FEAT_NAMES = ["MolWt", "TPSA", "NumHDonors", "NumHAcceptors", ...
              "NumRotatableBonds", "RingCount", "FractionCSP3", "HeavyAtomCount"];
N_FEATS    = numel(FEAT_NAMES);
rawTbl = readtable(DATA_FILE, TextType="string");
logInfo("Loaded %d entries from %s", height(rawTbl), DATA_FILE); %[output:01648a64]
%[text] Retrieve the ALogP column (may be read as numeric or string by the parser).
if isnumeric(rawTbl.ALogP)
    alogpVec = rawTbl.ALogP;
else
    alogpVec = str2double(rawTbl.ALogP);
end
%[text] Parse SMILES and calculate descriptors.
nRaw  = height(rawTbl);
X_all = nan(nRaw, N_FEATS);
y_all = nan(nRaw, 1);
valid = false(nRaw, 1);
for k = 1:nRaw
    if isnan(alogpVec(k)), continue; end      % Skip if ALogP is missing
    try
        mol = emk.mol.fromSmiles(rawTbl.SMILES(k));
        s   = emk.descriptor.calculate(mol, FEAT_NAMES);
        row = zeros(1, N_FEATS);
        for d = 1:N_FEATS
            row(d) = s.(FEAT_NAMES(d));
        end
        X_all(k, :) = row;
        y_all(k)    = alogpVec(k);
        valid(k)    = true;
    catch ME
        logWarn("Skipping %s: %s", rawTbl.Name(k), ME.message);
    end
end
logInfo("Descriptor calculation completed for %d / %d molecules", sum(valid), nRaw); %[output:10d53282]
X        = X_all(valid, :);    % Nx8 feature matrix (raw data, non-standardized)
y        = y_all(valid);       % Nx1 target variable vector (ALogP)
molNames = rawTbl.Name(valid);
nMols    = sum(valid);
logInfo("Dataset: Analyzed %d / %d molecules", nMols, nRaw); %[output:11cd0061]
logInfo("ALogP range: %.2f to %.2f (mean=%.2f, std=%.2f)", ... %[output:group:31e567c1] %[output:7224ebbe]
    min(y), max(y), mean(y), std(y)); %[output:group:31e567c1] %[output:7224ebbe]
%[text] Check the first 5 rows in table format.
prevN = min(5, nMols);
prevTbl = array2table(X(1:prevN, :), VariableNames=cellstr(FEAT_NAMES));
prevTbl.ALogP = y(1:prevN);
prevTbl.Name  = molNames(1:prevN);
prevTbl = movevars(prevTbl, "Name", Before=1);
disp(prevTbl); %[output:7f78bc98]
%%
%[text] ## Section 2: Exploring LogP Distribution
%[text] With descriptor calculation complete, we next examine the distribution of the target variable ALogP before fitting any model. Understanding the data upfront leads to better model interpretation.
%[text] ### Why Check the Target Variable Before Modeling
%[text] Linear regression assumes that residuals (observed minus predicted) are approximately normally distributed. The target $y$ itself need not be normal, but knowing its shape matters:
%[text] - Severe skew can be addressed with a log or Box-Cox transform.
%[text] - Outliers in $y$ can disproportionately pull the OLS fit.
%[text] - The model's reliable prediction range is bounded by the range seen in training. \
%[text] Recall that Lipinski's Rule of Five requires $LogP \\leq 5$ for drug-likeness. We will check whether the FDA drug set falls within the expected range of $-2$ to $+5$.
figure("Name", "A03 LogP Distribution"); %[output:756c71b1]
tiledlayout(1, 2); %[output:756c71b1]
nexttile; %[output:756c71b1]
histogram(y, 20, FaceColor=[0.3 0.6 0.9]); %[output:756c71b1]
xlabel("ALogP"); ylabel("Frequency"); %[output:756c71b1]
title("Distribution of ALogP (FDA-approved drugs)"); %[output:756c71b1]
xline(mean(y),   "--r", sprintf("mean=%.1f",   mean(y)),   LabelHorizontalAlignment="right"); %[output:756c71b1]
xline(median(y), "--g", sprintf("median=%.1f", median(y)), LabelHorizontalAlignment="left"); %[output:756c71b1]
grid on; %[output:756c71b1]
nexttile; %[output:756c71b1]
scatter(y, X(:, strcmp(cellstr(FEAT_NAMES), "TPSA")), 30, [0.3 0.6 0.9], ... %[output:756c71b1]
    "filled", MarkerFaceAlpha=0.6); %[output:756c71b1]
xlabel("ALogP"); ylabel("TPSA (A^2)"); %[output:756c71b1]
title(sprintf("TPSA vs ALogP  r=%.2f", corr(y, X(:, strcmp(cellstr(FEAT_NAMES), "TPSA"))))); %[output:756c71b1]
grid on; %[output:756c71b1]
logInfo("ALogP: mean=%.2f, median=%.2f, standard deviation=%.2f, skewness=%.2f", ... %[output:group:58dda663] %[output:99d34a21]
    mean(y), median(y), std(y), skewness(y)); %[output:group:58dda663] %[output:99d34a21]
%[text] Display scatter plots of each feature and ALogP in a 2x4 grid.
%[text] Check the sign and magnitude of the Pearson correlation coefficient $r$ for each panel.
%[text] $r \> 0$ means "as the descriptor increases, LogP rises," $r \< 0$ means "as the descriptor increases, LogP decreases."
figure("Name", "A03 Feature-LogP Scatter Plots"); %[output:7c4f25df]
for f = 1:N_FEATS
    subplot(2, 4, f); %[output:7c4f25df]
    scatter(X(:, f), y, 20, [0.2 0.5 0.8], "filled", MarkerFaceAlpha=0.5);
    xlabel(FEAT_NAMES(f)); ylabel("ALogP");
    r = corr(X(:, f), y);
    title(sprintf("r=%.2f", r));
    grid on;
end
sgtitle("8 Descriptors vs ALogP"); %[output:7c4f25df]
%%
%[text] ## Section 3: Linear Regression (fitlm)
%[text] With the distribution characterized, we now build the simplest baseline: multiple linear regression. Coefficients are directly interpretable, making linear models the natural starting point before trying more complex alternatives.
%[text] ### Multiple Regression Formula and Implementation
%[text] The linear QSAR model predicts LogP as a weighted sum of descriptors.
%[text] $\\hat{y} = b(0) + b(1) \\times MolWt + b(2) \\times TPSA + \\cdots + b(8) \\times HeavyAtomCount$
%[text] Here, $\\hat{y}$ denotes the predicted LogP, $b(0)$ the intercept, and $b(1)$ through $b(8)$ the coefficients for each descriptor.
%[text] Coefficients are estimated using Ordinary Least Squares (OLS).
%[text] OLS finds the coefficients that minimize the sum of squared residuals $\\sum\_i (y(i) - \\hat{y}(i))^2$.
%[text] Standardizing features (z-score transformation) before fitting allows comparison of the "relative influence" of each descriptor by coefficient magnitude.
%[text] The standardization formula is $z = \\frac{x - \\mu}{\\sigma}$, where $\\mu$ is the mean and $\\sigma$ is the standard deviation.
%[text] The main diagnostic indicators output by `fitlm` are as follows.
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Indicator | Meaning |
%[text] | --- | --- |
%[text] | $R^2$ | Proportion of variance explained (values evaluated on the training set are optimistic) |
%[text] | RMSE | Root Mean Square Error (average prediction error in LogP units) |
%[text] | p-value | Statistical test of whether the coefficient is significantly different from zero |
%[text] | Residuals | Difference between observed and predicted values. Should be normally distributed without patterns |
%[text:table]
%[text] Standardize the features (convert to mean 0, standard deviation 1).
Xmean = mean(X, 1);
Xstd  = std(X,  0, 1);
Xstd(Xstd < 1e-12) = 1;      % Prevent division by zero for constant descriptors
Xs    = (X - Xmean) ./ Xstd;  % Nx8 standardized feature matrix
%[text] Fit a linear model using all training data.
ftTbl = array2table(Xs, VariableNames=cellstr(FEAT_NAMES));
ftTbl.ALogP = y;
lmModel = fitlm(ftTbl, "ALogP ~ " + strjoin(FEAT_NAMES, " + "));
logInfo("Linear Model (Training): R2=%.3f  RMSE=%.3f LogP units", ... %[output:group:0f5445b7] %[output:107de7dc]
    lmModel.Rsquared.Ordinary, lmModel.RMSE); %[output:group:0f5445b7] %[output:107de7dc]
disp(lmModel); %[output:1c26d8fb]
%[text] Check the plot of observed vs predicted values, residual distribution, and standardized coefficients in three panels.
yPred_lm  = predict(lmModel, ftTbl);
residuals = y - yPred_lm;
figure("Name", "A03 Linear Model Diagnostics"); %[output:7a3fb922]
set(gcf, "Position", [100 100 1100 380]); %[output:7a3fb922]
tiledlayout(1, 3); %[output:7a3fb922]
nexttile; %[output:7a3fb922]
scatter(y, yPred_lm, 30, [0.3 0.6 0.9], "filled", MarkerFaceAlpha=0.7); %[output:7a3fb922]
hold on; %[output:7a3fb922]
refLim = [min(y)-0.5, max(y)+0.5];
plot(refLim, refLim, "--k", LineWidth=1.5); %[output:7a3fb922]
hold off; %[output:7a3fb922]
xlabel("Observed ALogP"); ylabel("Predicted ALogP"); %[output:7a3fb922]
title(sprintf("Linear Model\nR^2=%.3f  RMSE=%.3f", lmModel.Rsquared.Ordinary, lmModel.RMSE)); %[output:7a3fb922]
grid on; %[output:7a3fb922]
nexttile; %[output:7a3fb922]
histogram(residuals, 20, FaceColor=[0.9 0.5 0.3]); %[output:7a3fb922]
xlabel("Residuals (Observed - Predicted)"); ylabel("Frequency"); %[output:7a3fb922]
title("Residual Distribution"); %[output:7a3fb922]
xline(0, "--k"); grid on; %[output:7a3fb922]
nexttile; %[output:7a3fb922]
[sortCoeff, sortOrd] = sort(lmModel.Coefficients.Estimate(2:end), "descend");
barh(fliplr(sortCoeff), FaceColor=[0.3 0.6 0.9]); %[output:7a3fb922]
yticks(1:N_FEATS); %[output:7a3fb922]
yticklabels(fliplr(cellstr(FEAT_NAMES(sortOrd)))); %[output:7a3fb922]
xlabel("Standardized Coefficients"); xline(0, "k"); %[output:7a3fb922]
title("Regression Coefficients (Standardized)"); grid on; %[output:7a3fb922]
logInfo("Descriptor with the strongest positive influence: %s (Coefficient=%.3f)", ... %[output:group:20ca5243] %[output:2ef2a326]
    FEAT_NAMES(sortOrd(1)), sortCoeff(1)); %[output:group:20ca5243] %[output:2ef2a326]
logInfo("Descriptor with the strongest negative influence: %s (Coefficient=%.3f)", ... %[output:group:887dc6c6] %[output:2cd27f22]
    FEAT_NAMES(sortOrd(end)), sortCoeff(end)); %[output:group:887dc6c6] %[output:2cd27f22]
%[text] Recall the chemical predictions from Section 1 and check whether the coefficient signs agree. After standardization, descriptors with larger $|b(j)|$ exert stronger influence on LogP in this dataset.
%[text] Positive coefficients mean the descriptor raises LogP; negative coefficients mean it lowers LogP. In particular, verify that TPSA and HBD carry negative coefficients -- consistent with their role in increasing polarity.
%[text] If the residual histogram is approximately symmetric and bell-shaped, the normality assumption of linear regression holds.
%%
%[text] ## Section 4: Random Forest Regression (fitrensemble)
%[text] With the linear baseline established, we now try Random Forest, which can capture nonlinear structure-activity relationships.
logSection("A03", "Section 4: Random Forest Regression (fitrensemble)", "Analytics L3"); %[output:312f2f34]
%[text] Section 5 provides a fair comparison of both models via cross-validation.
%[text] ### Mechanism of Random Forest
%[text] Random Forest (Breiman 2001) is an ensemble learning method that combines multiple decision trees.
%[text] Construct $B$ trees using the following steps:
%[text] 1. Create $B$ bootstrap samples (random sampling with replacement) from the training data.
%[text] 2. Fit a decision tree to each sample. At each split, consider only $m$ randomly selected features (default: $m = \\lfloor p/3 \\rfloor$).
%[text] 3. Predictions are made by averaging the outputs of the $B$ trees. \
%[text] The table below summarizes key advantages of Random Forest over linear regression.
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Feature | Description |
%[text] | --- | --- |
%[text] | Nonlinear relationships | Tree splits are nonlinear, capturing curvilinear relationships between descriptors and LogP |
%[text] | Interactions | Automatically learns the combined effects of two or more descriptors |
%[text] | Feature importance | Quantifies each descriptor's contribution from impurity reduction (MDI) at splits |
%[text] | Robustness to outliers | Trees use rank-based splits, making them less sensitive to outliers |
%[text:table]
%[text] Note that the training $R^2$ of Random Forest is very optimistic (because trees can memorize data).
%[text] It is crucial to evaluate using cross-validation (Section 5).
%[text] Feature importance (MDI: Mean Decrease in Impurity) is calculated as the sum of "variance reduction x sample proportion at the node" for all splits using feature $j$.
%[text] A larger value indicates that the descriptor contributes more to the prediction.
rfModel = fitrensemble(Xs, y, ...
    Method="Bag", ...
    NumLearningCycles=200, ...
    Learners=templateTree(MinLeafSize=3));
yPred_rfTrain  = predict(rfModel, Xs);
ss_res_rf      = sum((y - yPred_rfTrain).^2);
ss_tot         = sum((y - mean(y)).^2);
r2_rf_train    = 1 - ss_res_rf / ss_tot;
rmse_rf_train  = sqrt(mean((y - yPred_rfTrain).^2));
logInfo("Random Forest (Training, Optimistic): R2=%.3f  RMSE=%.3f", ... %[output:group:27dbcd87] %[output:5a0ff87f]
    r2_rf_train, rmse_rf_train); %[output:group:27dbcd87] %[output:5a0ff87f]
logInfo("Note: RF training metrics are optimistic. Check generalization performance in Section 5 CV"); %[output:95902564]
%[text] Visualize feature importance with a bar graph and check observed vs predicted values in the training data.
importances = predictorImportance(rfModel);
[sortedImp, sortOrdRF] = sort(importances, "descend");
refLim = [min(y)-0.5, max(y)+0.5];   % Redefine for independent execution from Section 3
figure("Name", "A03 Random Forest"); %[output:4e674709]
tiledlayout(1, 2); %[output:4e674709]
nexttile; %[output:4e674709]
barh(fliplr(sortedImp), FaceColor=[0.4 0.7 0.4]); %[output:4e674709]
yticks(1:N_FEATS); %[output:4e674709]
yticklabels(fliplr(cellstr(FEAT_NAMES(sortOrdRF)))); %[output:4e674709]
xlabel("Feature Importance (MDI)"); %[output:4e674709]
title("RF Feature Importance"); %[output:4e674709]
grid on; %[output:4e674709]
nexttile; %[output:4e674709]
scatter(y, yPred_rfTrain, 30, [0.4 0.7 0.4], "filled", MarkerFaceAlpha=0.7); %[output:4e674709]
hold on; %[output:4e674709]
plot(refLim, refLim, "--k", LineWidth=1.5); %[output:4e674709]
hold off; %[output:4e674709]
xlabel("Observed ALogP"); ylabel("Predicted (RF, Training)"); %[output:4e674709]
title(sprintf("RF Training  R^2=%.3f  RMSE=%.3f", r2_rf_train, rmse_rf_train)); %[output:4e674709]
grid on; %[output:4e674709]
logInfo("RF Most Important Feature: %s  Least Importance: %s", ... %[output:group:3cf95baa] %[output:576b7b7a]
    FEAT_NAMES(sortOrdRF(1)), FEAT_NAMES(sortOrdRF(end))); %[output:group:3cf95baa] %[output:576b7b7a]
%[text] Notice that the training $R^2$ is very high -- a hallmark of overfitting. Random forest trees can memorize training data when left unconstrained. Section 5 measures actual performance on held-out data via cross-validation.
%%
%[text] ## Section 5: Comparison by 5-Fold Cross-Validation
%[text] With both models built, we now reach the crucial step: fair comparison via cross-validation. Training error is always optimistic -- cross-validation estimates how well each model generalizes to unseen molecules.
%[text] ### Mechanism of $k$-Fold Cross-Validation
%[text] $k$-Fold cross-validation is a method to estimate generalization error by dividing data into $k$ groups (folds).
%[text] The procedure is as follows.
%[text] 1. Divide $n$ molecules into $k$ equal folds.
%[text] 2. Leave fold $i$ ($i = 1, \\ldots, k$) as the "test set" and train on the remaining data.
%[text] 3. Make predictions for the molecules in fold $i$ (since this fold is not used during training, it provides a fair evaluation).
%[text] 4. Aggregate predictions from all folds to calculate CV evaluation metrics. \
%[text] $k=5$ is a standard choice, training on 80% of the data per fold.
%[text] Recall the three metrics we will use to evaluate model quality.
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Metric | Formula | Interpretation |
%[text] | --- | --- | --- |
%[text] | $R^2$ | $1 - \\frac{\\sum\_i(y(i)-\\hat{y}(i))^2}{\\sum\_i(y(i)-\\bar{y})^2}$ | 1=perfect prediction, 0=same as mean prediction, negative=below mean |
%[text] | RMSE | $\\sqrt{\\frac{1}{n}\\sum\_i(y(i)-\\hat{y}(i))^2}$ | Error in LogP units (high impact of outliers) |
%[text] | MAE | $\\frac{1}{n}\\sum\_i|y(i)-\\hat{y}(i)|$ | Error in LogP units (robust to outliers) |
%[text:table]
%[text] A good QSAR regression model typically achieves CV $R^2 \> 0.6$.
%[text] CV $R^2 \> 0.8$ is considered excellent for drug-like property prediction.
K_FOLDS = 5;
rng(42);
cv = cvpartition(nMols, KFold=K_FOLDS);
yCV_lm = nan(nMols, 1);   % out-of-fold predictions: linear model
yCV_rf = nan(nMols, 1);   % out-of-fold predictions: random forest
for fold = 1:K_FOLDS
    trainIdx = training(cv, fold);
    testIdx  = test(cv, fold);
    % Linear model for this fold
    trTbl = array2table(Xs(trainIdx, :), VariableNames=cellstr(FEAT_NAMES));
    trTbl.ALogP = y(trainIdx);
    lm_f  = fitlm(trTbl, "ALogP ~ " + strjoin(FEAT_NAMES, " + "));
    teTbl = array2table(Xs(testIdx, :), VariableNames=cellstr(FEAT_NAMES));
    yCV_lm(testIdx) = predict(lm_f, teTbl);
    % Random Forest for this fold
    rf_f = fitrensemble(Xs(trainIdx, :), y(trainIdx), ...
        Method="Bag", NumLearningCycles=200, ...
        Learners=templateTree(MinLeafSize=3));
    yCV_rf(testIdx) = predict(rf_f, Xs(testIdx, :));
end
logInfo("%d-Fold CV completed", K_FOLDS); %[output:99a7c082]
%[text] Calculating CV evaluation metrics (generating a structure with an anonymous function).
computeMetrics = @(yt, yp) struct( ...
    "R2",   1 - sum((yt-yp).^2) / sum((yt-mean(yt)).^2), ...
    "RMSE", sqrt(mean((yt-yp).^2)), ...
    "MAE",  mean(abs(yt-yp)));
cv_lm = computeMetrics(y, yCV_lm);
cv_rf = computeMetrics(y, yCV_rf);
logInfo("--- %d-Fold CV Results ---", K_FOLDS); %[output:9679ffb8]
logInfo("Linear Model:     R2=%.3f  RMSE=%.3f  MAE=%.3f", ... %[output:group:3bd74854] %[output:61e3d55d]
    cv_lm.R2, cv_lm.RMSE, cv_lm.MAE); %[output:group:3bd74854] %[output:61e3d55d]
logInfo("Random Forest: R2=%.3f  RMSE=%.3f  MAE=%.3f", ... %[output:group:5e1210a0] %[output:5d573881]
    cv_rf.R2, cv_rf.RMSE, cv_rf.MAE); %[output:group:5e1210a0] %[output:5d573881]
logInfo("Overfitting Gap (RF): Training RMSE=%.3f  CV RMSE=%.3f", ... %[output:group:6e2f8744] %[output:024756a0]
    rmse_rf_train, cv_rf.RMSE); %[output:group:6e2f8744] %[output:024756a0]
%[text] ### Why might linear regression be superior in this case?
%[text] The target variable ALogP in this dataset is an estimate calculated by the Crippen-Wildman method (linear sum of atomic contributions).
%[text] Since the generation mechanism itself is linear, linear regression fits well with the data structure.
%[text] In a small dataset with $n=200$, the high flexibility of RF can easily lead to overfitting.
%[text] When using experimentally measured LogP (including nonlinear intermolecular interactions) as the target variable, RF may become superior.
%[text] An important lesson is that "a powerful model does not always win." Always use CV for model selection.
%[text] The scatter plots below compare actual vs. cross-validated predicted values for both models.
figure("Name", "A03 Cross-Validation Comparison"); %[output:094cae97]
tiledlayout(1, 2); %[output:094cae97]
nexttile; %[output:094cae97]
scatter(y, yCV_lm, 30, [0.3 0.6 0.9], "filled", MarkerFaceAlpha=0.7); %[output:094cae97]
hold on; plot(refLim, refLim, "--k", LineWidth=1.5); hold off; %[output:094cae97]
xlabel("Actual ALogP"); ylabel("CV Predicted ALogP"); %[output:094cae97]
title(sprintf("Linear Model (5-Fold CV)\nR^2=%.3f  RMSE=%.3f", cv_lm.R2, cv_lm.RMSE)); %[output:094cae97]
grid on; %[output:094cae97]
nexttile; %[output:094cae97]
scatter(y, yCV_rf, 30, [0.4 0.7 0.4], "filled", MarkerFaceAlpha=0.7); %[output:094cae97]
hold on; plot(refLim, refLim, "--k", LineWidth=1.5); hold off; %[output:094cae97]
xlabel("Actual ALogP"); ylabel("CV Predicted ALogP"); %[output:094cae97]
title(sprintf("Random Forest (5-Fold CV)\nR^2=%.3f  RMSE=%.3f", cv_rf.R2, cv_rf.RMSE)); %[output:094cae97]
grid on; %[output:094cae97]
%[text] The closer the scatter plot points are to the diagonal (ideal prediction line), the higher the prediction accuracy.
%[text] By tracking points far from the diagonal (molecules with large prediction errors), structural features of molecules that the model struggles with may become apparent.
%%
%[text] ## Section 6: Applying the Model to New Molecules
%[text] Cross-validation has identified our best model. We now apply it to predict LogP for molecules outside the training set.
%[text] ### Prediction Pipeline and Applicability Domain
%[text] The Applicability Domain (AD) refers to the range of chemical space where the model's predictions are reliable.
%[text] A QSAR model trained on FDA-approved drugs is most reliable for molecules similar to the training set (within the AD).
%[text] Here, we use the simplest AD check (range method).
%[text] When standardizing the descriptors of new molecules with the mean and standard deviation of the training set, if all features are $|z| \\leq 2$ (within 2 sigma of the training data), it is considered within the AD.
%[text] There are more rigorous AD methods (leverage-based or $k$-NN distance-based), but range checks are effective as a practical first screening.
%[text] Use CV as a "yardstick" for model selection, and improve prediction accuracy by using a model trained on all data for actual predictions.
%[text] Select the model based on CV $R^2$ and retrain with all data.
if cv_rf.R2 >= cv_lm.R2
    finalModel = fitrensemble(Xs, y, Method="Bag", NumLearningCycles=200, ...
        Learners=templateTree(MinLeafSize=3));
    modelLabel = "Random Forest";
    predictFn  = @(xS) predict(finalModel, xS);
else
    finalTbl   = array2table(Xs, VariableNames=cellstr(FEAT_NAMES));
    finalTbl.ALogP = y;
    finalModel = fitlm(finalTbl, "ALogP ~ " + strjoin(FEAT_NAMES, " + "));
    modelLabel = "Linear";
    predictFn  = @(xS) predict(finalModel, ...
        array2table(xS, VariableNames=cellstr(FEAT_NAMES)));
end
logInfo("Final model: %s (retrained with all %d molecules)", modelLabel, nMols); %[output:13f30487]
%[text] Predict LogP for 5 known molecules.
newSmiles = ["CCO", ...                              % Ethanol
             "c1ccccc1", ...                         % Benzene
             "CC(=O)Oc1ccccc1C(=O)O", ...           % Aspirin
             "CN1C=NC2=C1C(=O)N(C)C(=O)N2C", ...   % Caffeine
             "CC12CCC3C(C1CCC2O)CCC4=CC(=O)CCC34"]; % Testosterone
logInfo("Predicting LogP for %d new molecules:", numel(newSmiles)); %[output:63ad5231]
for k = 1:numel(newSmiles) %[output:group:926ae33d]
    try
        mol = emk.mol.fromSmiles(newSmiles(k));
        s   = emk.descriptor.calculate(mol, FEAT_NAMES);
        xNew = zeros(1, N_FEATS);
        for d = 1:N_FEATS
            xNew(d) = s.(FEAT_NAMES(d));
        end
        xNewS = (xNew - Xmean) ./ Xstd;   % Standardize with training statistics
        % Applicability Domain: 2-sigma range check (after standardization with training statistics, check if all features are |z| <= 2)
        inDomain = all(abs(xNewS) <= 2);
        domainStr = "OK";
        if ~inDomain, domainStr = "OUT-OF-DOMAIN"; end
        logpPred = predictFn(xNewS);
        logInfo("  %-46s -> LogP_pred=%5.2f  [%s]", newSmiles(k), logpPred, domainStr); %[output:8bcc40cd]
    catch ME
        logWarn("  Failed for %s: %s", newSmiles(k), ME.message);
    end
end %[output:group:926ae33d]
%[text] Recall that ethanol is highly water-soluble (low LogP) and benzene is lipophilic (high LogP). Check whether the predictions are consistent with this chemical intuition.
%[text] Molecules flagged as OUT-OF-DOMAIN fall outside the chemical space spanned by the training set, so predictions for them carry lower reliability.
%[text] ## Summary
%[text] - Standardize features to z-scores before linear regression to obtain interpretable coefficients.
%[text] - Training error is always optimistic. Estimate generalization performance with cross-validation.
%[text] - Random Forest captures nonlinear effects, but linear models may prevail with small data.
%[text] - Always check the applicability domain before trusting QSAR predictions. \

